post_text:
Congratulations to Wheeling Park High School‚Äôs Jenna Bopp!

The state-champion Patriot swimmer will be heading to Marshall University next fall following her graduation from Wheeling Park High School in 2021. Bopp said she is excited to continue her academic and athletic pursuits as a member of the Thundering Herd, but she noted that she still has much to look forward to and much to accomplish in her senior year at The Palace on the Hill.

Last February, Bopp won her first West Virginia championship in the 100-yard breast stroke. She looks forward to continuing her academic and athletic success in her final year as a Wheeling Park Patriot. Bopp is the daughter of Diann and Victor Bopp.

#experienceTHEPARK
#TogetherWeAchieve

shared_text:
Elm Grove Elementary Dragons
August 31 at 3:12 PM ¬∑

Attention Elm Grove families:
Device & material pick up for grades 1st through 5th is scheduled for Thursday, September 3rd from 4:30-6:30 pm.
In-person and remote students are encouraged to attend. An OCS Technology Device Loan Agreement must be signed by the parent/guardian in order to receive your child's device. This form is available on the OCS website. Copies of the form will also be available that evening.
* If you are a remote learner and not able to attend please call the school to make arrangements. 304-243-0363.
*If you are an in-person learner and cannot attend, the OCS Technology Device Loan Agreement will be sent home with your student on their first day of school. Once signed and returned, their electronic device will be permitted to come home with them.
*Pre-K and Kindergarten pick ups will be scheduled at a later date. TBD.

Please wear a mask and practice social distancing during this event.

Pick-Up locations: Elm Grove Elementary

1st grade - door #2
2nd grade - door #12
3rd grade - door #6
4th grade - door #11
5th grade - door #10

shared_text:
Ohio County Schools
July 29 at 5:39 PM ¬∑

Good evening! On July 27th, the Ohio County Schools Board of Education approved our re-entry plan for the 2020-2021 school year. So that we can continue our preparations for the new school year and so our families can begin to make arrangements, we wanted to explain the re-entry scenarios in more detail and provide access to the form where families will make their re-entry choice.

Below, you will find the link to the School Re-Entry Choice Form as well as a video that walks through the form and explains the in-school and at-home options in more detail. Please complete a separate form for each student you have attending Ohio County Schools. If you are unable to complete the form online, please call the Board of Education Office at (304) 243-0300 beginning on August 3rd to receive assistance completing your form.

Video Explanation: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ZfJURH9C3VAt6he2RqjLzxsPMXRlnF5M/view?usp=sharing

Link to Complete School Re-Entry Choice Form: https://forms.gle/cJmZ9SAph7DXyvst5

post_text:
Remember to pick up your meals this week at any of the locations below!

In order to maintain the wellbeing of our staff and our families picking up meals, please follow these safety guidelines at our meal distribution sites:

1. Stay in your vehicle!

2. Maintain social distance while alerting staff the number of meals needed.

3. We practice no contact meal distribution and cannot reach into your vehicle. Staff can put the number of meals requested on a cart for you to put into your vehicle with the window down. Again, please do not exit your vehicle.

4. Staff will sanitize carts between guests.

Thank you for your cooperation!

post_text:
‚ù§Ô∏è Social Skill of the Week ‚ù§Ô∏è

This week, we will learn about GRATITUDE!

Feeling and expressing GRATITUDE can help improve your overall mental health. It's important to take time to allow yourself to feel that gratitude and express it to the person, place, or thing that brought that feeling to you.

Sometimes, when we are feeling down, it is hard to find things for which to be grateful. We feel the burden of negativity and "bad luck". However, we can quickly find GRATITUDE by reminding ourselves of the people who love us, our needs that are met, and the things that make us happy.

Show some gratitude today, and follow Mrs. Seidler‚Äôs Office on Facebook for more info!

Wheeling Park High School continues to work toward meeting its graduates' desire to have an in-person commencement ceremony. However, in an abundance of caution, school officials have decided to relocate graduation to Wheeling Island Stadium. Graduation will still be held at 3 p.m. on Aug. 2. There will be two tickets per graduate, and there will be social distancing. Additional details, such as a rain date, are still being coordinated, but that information will be shared as soon as possible. Graduation practice is at 3 p.m. on July 30 at Wheeling Island Stadium.
#experienceTHEPARK
#TogetherWeAchieve

post_text:
‚ù§Ô∏è Social Skill of the Week ‚ù§Ô∏è

This week, we will learn about COPING SKILLS! These are strategies you can use to help you calm down when you are feeling angry, sad, and overwhelmed.

When you use healthy coping skills, you don't only feel better but are able to think more clearly to better handle the situation.

Coping skills can be either negative or positive. The best way to decipher between the two is to ask yourself:

‚≠êÔ∏èIs this healthy?
‚≠êÔ∏èIs this safe?
‚≠êÔ∏èIs this helpful?

If you can't confidently answer yes to all of these questions, it would probably be best to choose a better coping skill.

post_text:
Ohio County Schools and Usborne Books & More have joined together to get books to students during the time they need it most: summer! The goal was to be able to purchase as many books as possible to give to the kids with the weekly meal distribution from Ohio County Schools. Focusing on books for students in grades Pre-K to third grade, Ohio County Schools asked for 100, $5 donations. Usborne Books & More matched these donations by 50 percent to purchase brand new books for students.

They have exceeded their goal and raised $1,382 in monetary donations. With the 50 percent match and other contributions, a total of $2,237 in books was purchased for the students of Ohio County Schools!

Thank you to Usborne Books & More and Educational Field Representative Katy Kurtz.

#TogetherWeAchieve

Usborne Books & More matched these donations by 50 percent to purchase brand new books for students.

They have exceeded their goal and raised $1,382 in monetary donations. With the 50 percent match and other contributions, a total of $2,237 in books was purchased for the students of Ohio County Schools!

Thank you to Usborne Books & More and Educational Field Representative Katy Kurtz.

#TogetherWeAchieve

post_text:
‚ù§Ô∏è Social Skill of the Week ‚ù§Ô∏è

This week is all about being an UPSTANDER!

An upstander is someone who stands up when they see something wrong. You can be an upstander by saying something, doing something, or telling someone. But what does that mean?

Say something to the bully:
Stop. - We don't do that. - That's not cool. - You aren't being nice

Say something to the other person:
Are you ok? - Want to sit together at lunch? - Don't listen to them.

Do something:
Change the subject - Ask about homework - Don't laugh or play along.

Tell someone:
Tell an adult - Tell a parent - Tell a teacher - Tell a coach!

Follow Mrs. Seidler‚Äôs Office on Facebook for more information!

If you have not received your P-EBT by June 30, 2020, please use this link www.emergencymealsurvey.com/wv to submit a claims resolution form.

This form will be available June 30 ‚Äì July 17, 2020.

This form is not an application for benefits, but will allow a formal ticket to be created for your individual case if you have still not received full benefits by that time.
If you have additional questions or need more information regarding P-EBT please visit https://wvde.us/covid19/wv-pebt/#update

Once the form closes and we receive the file from DHHR with the undeliverable cards we will be sending out a new file for counties to update. This file will most likely not be available until sometime in August.

post_text:
Randy McCardle has been selected as the 2020-2021 Ohio County Schools Transportation Department Employee of the Year.

McCardle has served for 43 years in the Ohio County Schools Transportation Department. McCardle is the bus garage coordinator and a mechanic. Ohio County Schools Operations Director Brian Harto said McCardle has extensive knowledge in multiple fields.

‚ÄúRandy is an encyclopedia on legs,‚Äù Harto said. ‚ÄúWhether it‚Äôs the history of Ohio County Schools or the school system‚Äôs bus fleet, he knows it all. He is a steady force in a job that is fast paced and continually changing as the buses roll during the year.‚Äù

Harto said McCardle is well liked by the Transportation Department staff members. He said McCardle is a dedicated worker.

‚ÄúHe can bring a laugh to the conversation,‚Äù Harto said. ‚ÄúBut, he is always willing to help in any situation. He will step in and drive a bus or help out his fellow mechanics on a project. Randy is an exceptional employee.‚Äù

Jason McGlumphy has been selected as the 2020-2021 Triadelphia Middle School Service Personnel Employee of the Year.

McGlumphy is the school‚Äôs head custodian. He has served 13 years for Ohio County Schools, and he has worked at Triadelphia Middle School for the past three years. Triadelphia Middle School Principal Ann Coleman said McGlumphy has a positive attitude, and he is reliable. She said she appreciates his ability to get along with a large staff and complete assignments in a pleasant and responsible manner.

‚ÄúJason is always smiling,‚Äù Coleman said. ‚ÄúWe can count on him to take care of all assigned tasks in a kind and caring way. He sees what needs done in advance, and does it. He can rally the troops and get others to follow his lead when work is needed.‚Äù

Coleman noted that, as a father of five children, McGlumphy understands children, and he can make their day special with a greeting in the lunch room or in the hallways. She said McGlumphy is a valuable member of the Triadelphia Middle School staff.

Christa Davis has been selected as the 2020-2021 Warwood Middle School Service Personnel Employee of the Year.

Davis is a Paraprofessional/Autism Mentor. She has been employed with Ohio County Schools for 14 years. Davis has served at Warwood for four years. Warwood Principal Joey Subasic said Davis is excellent in meeting the needs of students, but her impact goes far beyond that.

‚ÄúShe volunteers for many of the middle school activities and after school events,‚Äù Subasic said. ‚ÄúPlus, she supports all the student and school-wide initiatives. She gets along really well the staff, and she regularly works with teachers in the classrooms‚Äù

Subasic said Davis has many talents outside of her career. She enjoys singing and plays multiple instruments. Davis is also a writer. She has written a book intended for middle-school aged students that will be released this fall.

Here are some quick troubleshooting tips:

-Having difficulty viewing videos? Try right clicking and opening in a new tab
-Having trouble with content loading? Make sure you are signed into your child‚Äôs gmail account instead of a personal one

If you have technical difficulties that aren‚Äôt fixed by those tips, please reach out at instruction@wphs.ohio.k12.wv.us.

If you haven‚Äôt received your introduction email, please check your spam folder!

Thanks again for your patience!

post_text:
Ohio County Schools‚Äô partnership with Usborne Books & More is greatly benefitting the school system‚Äôs students.

Usborne Books & More Educational Services Representative Katy Kurtz said Thursday that $1,350 has been raised in a book drive to benefit Ohio County Schools students. UBAM has agreed to match 50 percent of that total, so $2,025 will be used for the purchase of reading materials.

Kurtz said the books will go to students in kindergarten through third grade, and she thanked donors for their contributions. Kurtz said she hopes to continue to bring in donations for additional books in the coming weeks. If you would like to contribute, you can do so here, https://linktr.ee/katysbooknook

Ohio County Schools Student Services Director Raquel McLeod thanked Kurtz and Usborne Books & More for efforts on behalf of the school system‚Äôs students. She said the children love the books, and they are something that the children can share with their families.

April Panas has been selected as Ritchie Elementary School‚Äôs 2020-2021 Teacher of the Year.
Panas is a third grade teacher at Ritchie Elementary School. She has served in Ohio County Schools for 16 years, and she has been at Ritchie for the past 13 years. Panas is also a tutor for students in grades K-8.
Ritchie Elementary School Principal John Jorden described Panas as a committed teacher. He said her love of teaching is apparent.
‚ÄúShe is considerate of all of her students‚Äô needs,‚Äù Jorden said. ‚ÄúApril‚Äôs love for her students, her plethora of skills, determination and professionalism make her the perfect choice for Ritchie's Teacher of the Year. April is an amazing person, and she is always there to support her co-workers and her students. She is truly passionate about her job, and she is an inspiration to all of her fellow teachers. April is an essential part of the Ritchie family.‚Äù
In her free time, Panas loves baking. She was a Zumba instructor for eight years, and she is the loving mother of chocolate lab, Abbie. Panas has been married to her husband, Steve, for 15 years.

post_text:
Sheila Little is the 2020-2021 Elm Grove Elementary School Service Personnel Employee of the Year.

Little is a cook/server at Elm Grove. She has been employed in Ohio County Schools for 13 years, and she has served at Elm Grove for 12 years. Dunlevy said Little will do whatever is necessary to make Elm Grove Elementary School the best it can be.
‚ÄúMs. Little is always willing to help,‚Äù Dunlevy said. ‚ÄúShe helped to clean the school after summer construction to get it ready for students. She'll stay after to serve students when lunch schedules get adjusted for field trips, and she gets along well with the students, faculty and staff.‚Äù

Dunlevy said Little is well liked by the students. He said she also takes the time to make special occasions more fun and exciting.

‚ÄúShe knows all the students and what they like to eat,‚Äù Dunlevy said. ‚ÄúShe's personable and talks to all students as they come thru the line. She dresses up for all the Holidays and helps decorate the kitchen and cafeteria for holidays. And, Ms. Little makes sure no student goes hungry.‚Äù

post_text:
Bobbi Jo McDaniel has been selected as the 2020-2021 Bethlehem Elementary School Service Personnel Employee of the Year.

McDaniel is the LPN/Aide at Bethlehem, and she just completed her first year of work at the school. She has been employed in Ohio County Schools for five years, after serving for four years at Madison Elementary School.

Bethlehem Elementary School Principal Stacy Dietz said McDaniel is always professional and helpful. In addition to being a nurse and an aide, she is also a lunch and recess supervisor, a bus chaperone and an arrival/dismissal greeter.

‚ÄúMs. McDaniel helps wherever and whenever it is needed,‚Äù Dietz said. ‚ÄúShe has a very reassuring demeanor, and she is eager to learn new things. She is flexible and works well under unique circumstances.‚Äù

Dietz said McDaniel has a good rapport with the students, teachers, staff members and parents of Bethlehem Elementary School.

‚ÄúShe has a pleasant and caring personality,‚Äù Dietz said. ‚ÄúMs. McDaniel is so knowledgeable, and she is so appreciated here at Bethlehem.‚Äù

shared_text:
Wheeling, WV City Government
May 11 at 4:46 PM ¬∑

Hey Wheeling! There are only a few weeks left in the Big 12 Census Challenge, so we really need to step up our responses! We have been consistent in that we are holding our own in 5th place and we have been for some time, but WE ARE WHEELING! We want that TOP spot! More important than the bragging rights that come with being the Big 12 Census Challenge Champion, though, is the fact that this year's Census data will determine federal funding for programs in our community for the NEXT 10 YEARS! So let's get to it, Wheeling! Did you know you can fill out the Census online, by phone or by mail? Visit 2020census.gov for details!

Our incredible community has been fast to act to help kids get the food and resources they need while we are not in school and navigating remote learning OCS is partnering with Usborne Books & More Educational Services Representative, Katy Kurtz, to get books into the hands of as many children in our community as possible and we need your help!

We are asking for 100, $5 donations to help reach our goal! Donations will be matched by 50% to purchase brand new books that will go straight to Ohio County Schools. We will include books with the food that we are providing to the amazing families right here in Ohio County. We are excited to spread the sunshine and hope that the kids can #justkeepreading!!

We would love your help!! If you are able to donate, you can send it to Katy through PayPal: https://www.paypal.me/katykurtz or Venmo @katysbooknook

Thank you!

We're pleased to announce that our joint application with the WV Department of Health & Human Resources for Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfer (P-EBT) cards to support child nutrition needs during COVID-19 pandemic has been approved by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. The implementation of P-EBT is in line with Governor Jim Justice's commitment to keep West Virginians safe and healthy during this national emergency, and to keep kids fed when schools are closed.

For more information on the P-EBT program, visit wvde.us/COVID19.

Swim Team - Boys Team Update...

The boys 400 relay of Leary, Kellas, Kuttan, and McCabe finish day 1 qualifying 4th for tomorrow!!!

We have two in the boys 100 fly...Max Kellas in 8th and Owen Leary in 11th! #justkeepswimming

And it continues...Devan Kuttan qualifies 3rd in the 200IM!!!!

With the start of the boys session...the boys medley relay has qualified 4th and of course they broke the school record. #nobigdeal

The 2020 Ohio Valley Sport Stacking Competition will be held Saturday at Woodsale Elementary School. The tournament will feature 70 stackers from five states and Canada. The event has been held for the past nine years at Woodsdale Elementary School where multiple world and state records have been set.
Woodsdale physical education teacher Mike Cook is the event director, and he thanked Hardee‚Äôs for sponsoring the event for the eighth consecutive year. Two of the area‚Äôs best stackers, Woodsdale fourth grader Timothy Hall and second grader Maggie Young, took part in a sport-stacking demonstration today at Hardee‚Äôs.

Victor Rouse, Jr. recently completed his graduation requirements for Wheeling Park High School at the Mountaineer Challenge Academy. Rouse, pictured with his mother, Heather Russell, plans to join the United States Navy.
There are eight core components of the Mountaineer Challenge Academy program. Cadets must successfully complete all eight components to graduate from the Academy. The core components are designed to educate and produce youth that will become productive members of the community upon graduation.

The eight core components are:
Academic Excellence
Life Coping Skills
Job Skills
Health and Hygiene
Responsible Citizenship
Service to the Community
Leadership/Followership
Physical Fitness
Congratulations Victor!!!
#experienceTHEPARK
#TogetherWeAchieve

Triadelphia Middle School
December 18, 2019 at 12:53 PM ¬∑

Thank you for supporting the Triadelphia Middle School Student Council Food Drive. Our staff, students, and families were able to collect over 700 can food items!

The food donation will go to the kitchen in McCrary Center's Transitional Living Program. Community meals are prepared and shared with the centers residents.

The Youth Services System works with youth from the ages of 17-21 to build life skills, education, and work experience for a solid foundation for becoming independent adults in our student community. The McCrary Center's Transitional Living Program works with youth aging out of foster care. Their services offer support, training and housing with the goal of independent living.

post_text:
Ohio County Sheriff‚Äôs Deputy Sgt. Chuck Kittle is going beyond the call of duty at Wheeling Park High School.
Kittle serves as a Prevention Resource Officer at Park, but he also visits Civics classes to discuss the U.S. Bill of Rights. He presents a lesson on police procedures as they pertain to the rights afforded to U.S. citizens.
Kittle primarily discusses the Fourth Amendment, which protects against unreasonable search and seizure. Kittle also explains probable cause and reasonable suspicion. Once these thresholds are met, he explains what actions police office may take. The students enjoy the discussions, and they find it interesting and educational.
#experienceTHEPARK
#TogetherWeAchieve

Courtney Moore is the new music teacher at Wheeling Middle School.
She is a graduate of West Virginia University. Moore was inspired by her own teachers to become an educator. She said she was reserved as a child, but her teachers always made her feel welcomed and challenged her to do her best. Moore loves teaching because she gets to share her passion for music with her students.
Moore was a student of Ohio County Schools, and she is excited to give back to her hometown. Outside of the classroom, she enjoys reading.
Welcome to Ohio County Schools, Ms. Moore!!
